[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] In computer science, a **ball tree**, **balltree** or **metric tree**, is a space partitioning data structure for organizing points in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] A ball tree partitions data points into a nested set of balls.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The resulting data structure has characteristics that make it useful for a number of applications, most notably nearest neighbor search.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] A ball tree is a binary tree in which every node defines a D-dimensional ball containing a subset of the points to be searched.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Each internal node of the tree partitions the data points into two disjoint sets which are associated with different balls.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] While the balls themselves may intersect, each point is assigned to one or the other ball in the partition according to its distance from the ball's center.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Each leaf node in the tree defines a ball and enumerates all data points inside that ball.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Each node in the tree defines the smallest ball that contains all data points in its subtree.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] This gives rise to the useful property that, for a given test point t outside the ball, the distance to any point in a ball B in the tree is greater than or equal to the distance from t to the surface of the ball.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Where $D^{B}(t)$ is the minimum possible distance from any point in the ball B to some point t.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Ball-trees are related to the M-tree, but only support binary splits, whereas in the M-tree each level splits m to $2m$ fold, thus leading to a shallower tree structure, therefore need fewer distance computations, which usually yields faster queries.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Furthermore, M-trees can better be stored on disk, which is organized in pages.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The M-tree also keeps the distances from the parent node precomputed to speed up queries.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Vantage-point trees are also similar, but they binary split into one ball, and the remaining data, instead of using two balls.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] A number of ball tree construction algorithms are available.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The goal of such an algorithm is to produce a tree that will efficiently support queries of the desired type (e.g. nearest-neighbor) in the average case.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The specific criteria of an ideal tree will depend on the type of question being answered and the distribution of the underlying data.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] However, a generally applicable measure of an efficient tree is one that minimizes the total volume of its internal nodes.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Given the varied distributions of real-world data sets, this is a difficult task, but there are several heuristics that partition the data well in practice.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] In general, there is a tradeoff between the cost of constructing a tree and the efficiency achieved by this metric.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] This section briefly describes the simplest of these algorithms.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] A more in-depth discussion of five algorithms was given by Stephen Omohundro.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The simplest such procedure is termed the "*k*-d Construction Algorithm", by analogy with the process used to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] This is an offline algorithm, that is, an algorithm that operates on the entire data set at once.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The tree is built top-down by recursively splitting the data points into two sets.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Splits are chosen along the single dimension with the greatest spread of points, with the sets partitioned by the median value of all points along that dimension.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Finding the split for each internal node requires linear time in the number of samples contained in that node, yielding an algorithm with time complexity $O(n\,\log \,n)$ , where *n* is the number of data points.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] An important application of ball trees is expediting nearest neighbor search queries, in which the objective is to find the k points in the tree that are closest to a given test point by some distance metric (e.g.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] A simple search algorithm, sometimes called KNS1, exploits the distance property of the ball tree.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] In particular, if the algorithm is searching the data structure with a test point *t*, and has already seen some point *p* that is closest to *t* among the points encountered so far, then any subtree whose ball is further from *t* than *p* can be ignored for the rest of the search.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] The ball tree nearest-neighbor algorithm examines nodes in depth-first order, starting at the root.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] During the search, the algorithm maintains a max-first priority queue (often implemented with a heap), denoted *Q* here, of the k nearest points encountered so far.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] If *B* is a leaf node, scan through every point enumerated in *B* and update the nearest-neighbor queue appropriately.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] If *B* is an internal node, call the algorithm recursively on *B'*s two children, searching the child whose center is closer to *t* first.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Return the queue after each of these calls has updated it in turn.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] Performing the recursive search in the order described in point 3 above increases likelihood that the further child will be pruned entirely during the search.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] In comparison with several other data structures, ball trees have been shown to perform fairly well on the nearest-neighbor search problem, particularly as their number of dimensions grows.
[src:vector-search-index/ball-tree] However, the best nearest-neighbor data structure for a given application will depend on the dimensionality, number of data points, and underlying structure of the data.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] The **cover tree** is a type of data structure in computer science that is specifically designed to facilitate the speed-up of a nearest neighbor search.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] It is a refinement of the Navigating Net data structure, and related to a variety of other data structures developed for indexing intrinsically low-dimensional data.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] The tree can be thought of as a hierarchy of levels with the top level containing the root point and the bottom level containing every point in the metric space.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] Each level *C* is associated with an integer value *i* that decrements by one as the tree is descended.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] Like other metric trees the cover tree allows for nearest neighbor searches in $O(\eta *\log {n})$ where $\eta$ is a constant associated with the dimensionality of the dataset and n is the cardinality.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] To compare, a basic linear search requires $O(n)$ , which is a much worse dependence on n .
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] However, in high-dimensional metric spaces the $\eta$ constant is non-trivial, which means it cannot be ignored in complexity analysis.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] Unlike other metric trees, the cover tree has a theoretical bound on its constant that is based on the dataset's expansion constant or doubling constant (in the case of approximate NN retrieval).
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] The bound on search time is $O(c^{12}\log {n})$ where c is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] Although cover trees provide faster searches than the naive approach, this advantage must be weighed with the additional cost of maintaining the data structure.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] In a naive approach adding a new point to the dataset is trivial because order does not need to be preserved, but in a cover tree it can take $O(c^{6}\log {n})$ time.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] However, this is an upper-bound, and some techniques have been implemented that seem to improve the performance in practice.
[src:vector-search-index/cover-tree] The cover tree uses implicit representation to keep track of repeated points.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] In computer science, **locality-sensitive hashing** (**LSH**) is a fuzzy hashing technique that hashes similar input items into the same "buckets" with high probability.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] The number of buckets is much smaller than the universe of possible input items.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since similar items end up in the same buckets, this technique can be used for data clustering and nearest neighbor search.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] It differs from conventional hashing techniques in that hash collisions are maximized, not minimized.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively, the technique can be seen as a way to reduce the dimensionality of high-dimensional data; high-dimensional input items can be reduced to low-dimensional versions while preserving relative distances between items.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Hashing-based approximate nearest-neighbor search algorithms generally use one of two main categories of hashing methods: either data-independent methods, such as locality-sensitive hashing (LSH); or data-dependent methods, such as locality-preserving hashing (LPH).
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Locality-preserving hashing was initially devised as a way to facilitate data pipelining in implementations of massively parallel algorithms that use randomized routing and universal hashing to reduce memory contention and network congestion.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] if it satisfies the following condition.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively it is possible to define an LSH family on a universe of items U endowed with a similarity function $\phi \colon U\times U\to [0,1]$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] In this setting, a LSH scheme is a family of hash functions H coupled with a probability distribution D over H such that a function $h\in H$ chosen according to D satisfies $Pr[h(a)=h(b)]=\phi (a,b)$ for each $a,b\in U$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a $(d_{1},d_{2},p_{1},p_{2})$ -sensitive family ${\mathcal {F}}$ , we can construct new families ${\mathcal {G}}$ by either the AND-construction or OR-construction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an AND-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an OR-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] We then say that for a hash function $g\in {\mathcal {G}}$ , $g(x)=g(y)$ if and only if $h_{i}(x)=h_{i}(y)$ for one or more values of i.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the easiest ways to construct an LSH family is by bit sampling.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] This approach works for the Hamming distance over d-dimensional vectors $\{0,1\}^{d}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Here, the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ of hash functions is simply the family of all the projections of points on one of the d coordinates, i.e., ${\mathcal {F}}=\{h\colon \{0,1\}^{d}\to \{0,1\}\mid h(x)=x_{i}{\text{ for some }}i\in \{1,\ldots ,d\}\}$ , where $x_{i}$ is the i th coordinate of x .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] A random function h from ${\mathcal {F}}$ simply selects a random bit from the input point.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, any two vectors $x,y$ with Hamming distance at most R collide under a random h with probability at least $P_{1}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Any $x,y$ with Hamming distance at least $cR$ collide with probability at most $P_{2}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Suppose U is composed of subsets of some ground set of enumerable items S and the similarity function of interest is the Jaccard index J.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] If π is a permutation on the indices of S, for $A\subseteq S$ let $h(A)=\min _{a\in A}\{\pi (a)\}$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each possible choice of π defines a single hash function h mapping input sets to elements of S.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Define the function family H to be the set of all such functions and let D be the uniform distribution.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given two sets $A,B\subseteq S$ the event that $h(A)=h(B)$ corresponds exactly to the event that the minimizer of π over $A\cup B$ lies inside $A\cap B$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] As h was chosen uniformly at random, $Pr[h(A)=h(B)]=J(A,B)\,$ and $(H,D)\,$ define an LSH scheme for the Jaccard index.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because the symmetric group on n elements has size n!, choosing a truly random permutation from the full symmetric group is infeasible for even moderately sized n.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because of this fact, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent" — a permutation family for which each element of the domain has equal probability of being the minimum under a randomly chosen π.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] It has been established that a min-wise independent family of permutations is at least of size $\operatorname {lcm} \{\,1,2,\ldots ,n\,\}\geq e^{n-o(n)}$ , and that this bound is tight.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because min-wise independent families are too big for practical applications, two variant notions of min-wise independence are introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most k.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Approximate min-wise independence differs from the property by at most a fixed ε.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] The encoding must be robust against intentional attacks.
