[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] The random projection method of LSH due to Moses Charikar called SimHash (also sometimes called arccos) uses an approximation of the cosine distance between vectors.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] The technique was used to approximate the NP-complete max-cut problem.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] The basic idea of this technique is to choose a random hyperplane (defined by a normal unit vector r) at the outset and use the hyperplane to hash input vectors.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given an input vector v and a hyperplane defined by r, we let $h(v)=\operatorname {sgn}(v\cdot r)$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, $h(v)=\pm 1$ depending on which side of the hyperplane v lies.
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] This way, each possible choice of a random hyperplane r can be interpreted as a hash function $h(v)$ .
[src:vector-search-index/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since the ratio between ${\frac {\theta (u,v)}{\pi }}$ and $1-\cos(\theta (u,v))$ is at least 0.439 when $\theta (u,v)\in [0,\pi ]$ , the probability of two vectors being on different sides of the random hyperplane is approximately proportional to the cosine distance between them.
