[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:vector-search-index/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
